 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/7/03 7:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=85>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  proposed changes to S.724</span><hr size=1> [ from John Wickman ]<br>
<br>
After the introduction of Senate Bill S724, a couple of questions on the bill indicated some rewording of the bill was required to maintain its intent. The changes are marked in red. These changes have been submitted to Senator Enzi's office.<br>
<br>
1) The first question was whether a propellant actually had to be tested and classified by the DOT as a flammable solid or 1.3 explosive or lower for the exemption to apply. It was never the intention of the bill to require testing of propellants in order for the exemption to apply as this would severely cripple amateur rocketry in America. The wording defining a non-detonable propellant has been changed to make this more clear using the definitions provided in the CFRs for flammable solid and 1.3 class explosive or lower.<br>
<br>
2) There was question on item (a) listing prohibited rocket cargos. The intention was that all of those items listed in (a) are gases. This has now been made clear in the revision. <br>
<br>
3) Two new prohibited cargos have been added to the list, they are poisonous biological or chemical agents.<br>
<br>
---<br>
see <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.space-rockets.com/724rev-a.html">www.space-rockets.com/724rev-a.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> for the marked-up bill<br>
<br>
- iz<br>
