 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/10/03 1:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=90>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Senator education is key</span><hr size=1> Congress does not empower the ATF to set weight limits on road flares, why should they do so for specific classes of propellant with properties known to present only a limited hazard?<br>
<br>
What is the responsibility they are discharging? <br>
<br>
Security?  APCP is no more a threat to security than gasoline, and is far less destructive.  The ATF has admitted that APCP does not explode, and cannot provide a single example of it being used to construct a weapon.  S.724 stipulates that a design or use with an intent to harm remains unlawful.  Construction of explosive devices from raw materials (e.g. fertilizer and fuel oil) is already covered under law.  Why single out APCP as the only raw material to limit due to it's potential for misuse?<br>
<br>
Safety?  The ATF is not charged with enforcing fire codes; that falls to the State and local AHJs, enforced by Fire Marshalls.  <br>
<br>
Senators, like any person unfamiliar with APCP, may have a natural concern.  But rather than answer those concerns with accurate information, the ATF has conducted a disinformation campaign designed to maintain their purview over it, so that they may &quot;contain&quot; hobby rocketry activities.  That is their objective.<br>
<br>
In truth the Senators expressed concern is that someone should be managing rocketry activities.  The facts are that someone is: the FAA, the BLM, the States and the local AHJ's.<br>
<br>
No, the answer is not weight limits.  The answer is education.<br>
<br>
We are doing our part, with the help of a sympathetic media, to educate the public.  And when we write letters which communicate the facts, we are doing our part to educate our elected representatives.<br>
<br>
This is where our focus must be.  Insisting on factually based, rational an objective decisions by our government.<br>
<br>
- iz    <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/11/03 8:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=91>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/zilla.gif" align=absmiddle>  FAA already addresses Senators concerns, no ATF is needed</span><hr size=1> accepting weight limits for truly *explosive* materials can't hurt us, and we do.  Explosive materials are already prohibited under S.724 (with the exception of small ejection charges).<br>
<br>
on what basis do you accept a weight limit on a non-explosive material?<br>
<br>
if Senators (under ATF provocation) have an issue with unlimited payload loft capacity and range, which is as much a function of rocket design and construction as propellant,   that would be under the purview of the FAA, not the ATF.<br>
<br>
the FAA already regulates altitude waivers that are granted or not following consideration of launch location <br>
