 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A> at: 6/12/03 8:41 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 98<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/14/03 1:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=96>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  how S.724 works</span><hr size=1> [ from John Wickman ]<br>
<br>
One of the first problems we faced in Dec. 2002 was whether to directly take APCP and all rocket propellants off the explosives list or simply go for an exemption. It was decided that an exemption was our best chance at getting the most support in congress as it did not legislate a victory for the NAR/TRA lawsuit.<br>
<br>
Black powder was specifically put on the explosives list by congress. The ATFE cannot take it off even if they wanted to, which they don't. However, congress gave a weight limit exemption for black powder when used for a certain purpose in the same law. They also gave a no weight limit exemption for small arms ammo and all its components, which was smokeless powder. There was no restriction on the use of the components or smokeless powder.<br>
<br>
If congress passes 724 without weight limits, it is not a statement by congress one way or the other as to whether APCP should be on the explosives list. It is a statement that certain rocket propellants when used in certain rockets should not be subjected to SEA regulations. However, if you put a weight limit in the law, now congress is making a statement as to how dangerous it perceives these propellants relative to black powder. If the weight limit is 10 lbs, congress says these propellants are five times more dangerous than black powder.<br>
<br>
Now some would argue that if congress passes 724 without a limit, doesn't it say congress thinks these propellants should be off the list? Not necessarily, as an example, congress gave an exemption for small arms ammo and its components before they were put on the list. This does make sense if you go to the definition of an explosive where the key defining criteria is &quot;the primary or common purpose of which is to function by explosion&quot;. Suppose sometime in the future, propane grills and heaters fade into history and some other fuel takes its place. At the same time, some group of terrorists bent on overthrowing the government start using propane bombs. If a large percentage of propane available in the US is used in these bombs, one could argue that propane should be on the explosives list based on congress's definition - &quot;the primary or common purpose of {propane] is to function by explosion&quot;. The idea of providing an exemption for a substance before it is placed on the list is in recognition that some items may move on or off the list depending on their common purpose.<br>
<br>
At least, that is how the explosives law was supposed to work. The ATFE ignores the definition of congress and just put anything that explodes on the list unless it has a vocal or powerful group to defend the substance and keep it off the list.<br>
<br>
John Wickman <br>
<br>
<br>
[ posted by iz ]<br>
